&lt;div class="md__image">
 &lt;img id="[241 398 361 261 27 339]" src="https://cloud.layer5.io/academy/98e16360-a366-4b78-8e0a-031da07fdacb/sks-advance/updates-theory.png" onclick="openModal(this.id)" alt="image" 
 class="md-image-responsive" />
&lt;/div>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>The details are explained in the video below.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Updates Praxis</title><link>https://cloud.layer5.io/academy/learning-paths/98e16360-a366-4b78-8e0a-031da07fdacb/sks-advance/concepts/content/updates-praxis/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://cloud.layer5.io/academy/learning-paths/98e16360-a366-4b78-8e0a-031da07fdacb/sks-advance/concepts/content/updates-praxis/</guid><description>&lt;h3 id="updates-praxis" class="heading-link">
 &lt;strong>Updates Praxis&lt;/strong>
 &lt;a href="#updates-praxis" class="heading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink to this heading">ðŸ”—&lt;/a>
&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>The &lt;strong>kubectl&lt;/strong> command provides rollout and update capabilities for containerized applications and the associated Kubernetes constructs. Users expect applications to be available all the time, and developers deploy new versions of them several times a day.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>The concept of rolling updates allows an update with zero downtime by incrementally updating Pods with new ones. With the command &lt;strong>&amp;gt; kubectl rollout &amp;hellip;,&lt;/strong> you then can check the status of your deployment. You can also undo your deployment in an unsuccessful rollout and set it back to an older version.&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>